Hi Fay,
&nbsp;
Thank you for your time on the call today, I appreciate your availability.
&nbsp;
As discussed, we observed the following output when testing connectivity from the sensor as per attached log&nbsp;
 [diag-shell@220001 pods]$ curl -vk https://FLEETSERVER:1443/
* Host FLEETSERVER:1443 was resolved.
* IPv6: (none)
* IPv4: FLEET_IP
*   Trying FLEETIP:1443...
* ALPN: curl offers h2,http/1.1
* TLSv1.3 (OUT), TLS handshake, Client hello (1):
* TLSv1.3 (IN), TLS handshake, Server hello (2):
* TLSv1.3 (OUT), TLS change cipher, Change cipher spec (1):
* TLSv1.3 (OUT), TLS handshake, Client hello (1) &nbsp;
Additionally, running openssl s_client -connect FLEETSERVER:1443 indicates a TLS inspection/handshake issue. However, we confirmed with your network team that there is no firewall block or SSL inspection rule in place for this traffic.
&nbsp;
To rule out a potential mismatch between the certificate CN and the sensor SSL name, we also tested the following command:
 corelight-client configuration update --fleet.server_sslname="" You confirmed that there is no mismatch between the Fleet certificate CN and the configured fleet.server_sslname.
&nbsp;
We also verified that the Fleet Manager certificate is valid until December 2026.
&nbsp;
As discussed, we have already collected the required logs using the following commands:
&nbsp;
On the Fleet Manager:
 sudo journalctl -u corelight-fleetd --since "3 hours ago" &gt; fleetd_last3hours.txt &nbsp;
On the Sensor:
 sudo timeout 10s tcpdump -i any -s0 -w capture.pcap 'port 1443' &amp; sleep 2; openssl s_client -connect &lt;fleet_host&gt;:1443 &nbsp;
Please share the generated files:
  fleetd_last3hours.txt  capture.pcap  &nbsp;
After receiving them, we will review the logs in detail and revert back with our findings. If necessary, we will also escalate the case to our engineering team for further investigation.
